===Verb===
{{en-verb|es}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To make a clashing sound.
#: ''The cymbals '''clashed'''.''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To cause to make a clashing sound.
#* '''2012''', Robert Lyndon, ''Hawk Quest''
#*: Thorfinn '''clashed''' his shield against Vallon's and swung his axe to hook Vallon's ankle.
# To come into violent [[conflict]].
#: ''Fans from opposing teams '''clashed''' on the streets after the game.''
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[argue]] angrily.
#: ''My parents often '''clashed''' about minor things, such as the cleaning or shopping [[rota]].''
# {{lb|en|intransitive|in games or sports}} To [[face]] each other in an important game.
#* {{quote-journal
|lang=en
|date=June 27, 2008
|author=
|title=Jones confirms Calzaghe showdown
|work=BBC Sport
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/boxing/7476878.stm
|page=
|passage=The veteran American legend claims he and Welsh two-weight world champion Calzaghe will '''clash''' on 20 September, probably at The MGM Grand in Las Vegas.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|of clothes, decor, colours}} To fail to look good together; to contrast unattractively; to fail to harmonize.
#: ''You can't wear that shirt! It '''clashes''' with your trousers.''
#: ''The hotel room was ugly, and the wallpaper '''clashed''' with the carpet.''
# {{lb|en|intransitive|of events}} To [[coincide]], to happen at the same time, thereby rendering it impossible to attend all.
#: ''I can't come to your wedding because it '''clashes''' with a friend's funeral.''
#: ''I wanted to take German, but it '''clashed''' with art on the timetable.''
# {{lb|en|intransitive|Scotland}} To [[chatter]] or [[gossip]].

